he representative of the whole nation and he''s the only lobbyist that all the one hundred and sixty million people in this country have.', 16121, 0), (420033, 'Trying to make the presidency work these days is like trying to sew buttons on a custard pie.', 65979, 0), (420034, 'Th'' prisidincy is th'' highest office in th'' gift iv th people. Th'' vice-prisidincy is th'' next highest an'' the lowest. It isn''t a crime exactly. Ye can''t be sint to jail f r it  but it''s a kind iv a disgrace.', 25260, 0), (420035, 'Seriously  I do not think I am fit for the presidency.', 1012, 0), (420036, 'An eminent American is reported to have said to friends who wished to put him forward  ''Gentlemen  let there be no mistake. I should make a good president  but a very bad candidate.''', 13904, 0), (420037, 'Well  I wouldn''t say that I was in the ''great'' class  but I had a great time while I was trying to be great.', 16121, 0), (420038, 'The presidency does not yield to definition. Like the glory of a morning sunrise  it can be experienced - it can not be told.', 4110, 0), (420039, 'When the president does it  that means it is not illegal.', 20900, 0), (420040, 'A president''s hardest task is not to do what''s right  but to know what''s right.', 1763, 0), (420041, 'Had I been chosen president again  I am certain I could not have lived another year.', 4179, 0), (420042, 'The four most miserable years of my life . . .', 4179, 0), (420043, 'If you are as happy  my dear sir  on entering this house as I am in leaving it and returning home  you are the happiest man in the country.', 65980, 0), (420044, 'I feel like the man who was tarred and feathered and ridden out of town on a rail. To the man who asked how he liked it he said: ''If it wasn''t for the honour of the thing  I''d rather walk.''', 1012, 0), (420045, 'The office of president requires the constitution of an athlete  the patience of a mother  the endurance of an early Christian.', 18461, 0), (420046, 'Within the first few 