e the most powerful drug used by mankind.', 843, 0), (421592, 'We should have a great many fewer disputes in the world if words were taken for what they are  the signs of our ideas only  and not for things themselves.', 2375, 0), (421593, 'Speaking words of endearment where words of comfort availed not.', 147, 0), (421594, 'Sticks and stones may break my bones  But words can never harm me.', 63196, 0), (421595, 'Words will build no walls.', 4891, 0), (421596, 'A word spoken in good season  how good it is!', 44178, 0), (421597, 'A word fitly spoken is like apples of gold in pictures of silver.', 44178, 0), (421598, 'The words of his mouth were smoother than butter  but war was in his heart  his words were softer than oil  yet were they drawn swords.', 5587, 0), (421599, 'One of our defects as a nation is a tendency to use what have been called "weasel words." When a weasel sucks eggs the meat is sucked out of the egg. If you use a "weasel word" after another there is nothing left of the other.', 1674, 0), (421600, 'My word fly up  my thoughts remain below: Words without thoughts never to heaven go.', 13, 0);
INSERT INTO quotes (id, content, author_id, views) VALUES (421601, 'A word to the wise is sufficient.', 21159, 0), (421602, 'Man does not live by words alone  despite the fact that sometimes he has to eat them.', 28686, 0), (421603, 'But yesterday the word of Caesar might Have stood against the world  now lies he there  And none so poor to do him reverence.', 13, 0), (421604, 'Taffeta phrases  silken terms precise  Three-piled hyperboles  spruce affectation  Figures pedantical.', 13, 0), (421605, 'I sometimes hold it half a sin To put in words the grief I feel  For words  like Nature  half reveal And half conceal the Soul within.', 62337, 0), (421606, 'He utters empty words  he utters sound without mind.', 1462, 0), (421607, 'You (Pindar) who possessed the talent of speaking much without saying anything.', 808, 0), (421608, 'For of all sad words of tongue or pen  The saddest are these: "It might have been!"', 997, 0), (421609, '''twas bryllig and the slithy toves Did gyre and gimble in the wabe  All mimsy were the borogoves  And the mome raths out grabe.', 1253, 0), (421610, 'A word is not the same with one writer as with another. One tears it from his guts. The other pulls it out of his overcoat pocket.', 9561, 0), (421611, 'Language is the Rubicon that divides man from beast.', 66123, 0), (421612, 'Dialect words - those terrible marks of the beast to the truly genteel.', 552, 0), (421613, 'Eloquence is the language of nature  and cannot be learned in the schools  but rhetoric is the creature of art  which he who feels least will most excel in.', 432, 0), (421614, 'For words  like Nature  half reveal And half conceal the Soul within.', 63203, 0), (421615, 'He multiplieth words without knowledge.', 5587, 0), (421616, 'If you were to make little fishes talk  they would talk like whales.', 2204, 0), (421617, 'In the beginning was the Word and the Word was with God  and the Word was God.', 5587, 0), (421618, 'Languages are the pedigree of nations.', 2087, 0), (421619, 'Let thy speech be short  comprehending much in few words.', 5587, 0), (421620, 'Letter-writing is the only device for combining solitude with good company.', 62558, 0), (421621, 'Man is a creature who lives not upon bread alone  but principally by catch words.', 449, 0), (421622, 'Many terms which have now dropped out of favour will be revived  and those that are at present respectable  will drop out  if useage so choose with whom resides the decision and the judgment and the code of speech.', 2542, 0), (421623, 'Numbers constitute the only universal language.', 7185, 0), (421624, 'Soft words are hard arguments.', 1348, 0), (421625, 'Thanks to words  we have been able to rise above the brutes  and thanks to words  we have often sunk to the level of the demons.', 1032, 0), (421626, 'The adjective is the banana peel of the parts of speech.', 8863, 0), (421627, 'The limits of my language are the limits of my mind. All I know is what I have words for.', 1163, 0), (421628, 'The art of translation lies less in knowing the other language than in knowing your own.', 62566, 0), (421629, 'The two most beautiful words in the English language are "cheque enclosed".', 201, 0), (421630, 'The medium is the message.', 2728, 0), (421631, 'The stroke of the whip maketh marks in the flesh  but the stroke of the tongue breaketh the bones. Many have fallen by the edge of the sword  but not so many as have fallen by the tongue.', 66124, 0), (421632, 'The thoughtless are rarely wordless.', 66125, 0), (421633, 'We must have a better word than "prefabricated"  why not "ready-made"?', 3621, 0), (421634, 'We must think things not words  or at least we must constantly translate our words into the facts for which they stand  if we are to keep to the real and the true.', 24754, 0), (421635, 'Words are the small change of thought.', 1952, 0), (421636, 'Words should be weighed and not counted.', 37426, 0), (421637, 'Since the concepts people live by are derived only from perceptions and from language and since the perceptions are received and interpreted only in light of earlier concepts  man comes pretty close to living in a house that language built.', 66126, 0), (421638, 'If a conceptual distinction is to be made  the machinery for making it ought to show itself in language. If a distinction cannot be made in language  it cannot be made conceptually.', 66127, 0), (421639, 'Often I am struck in amazement about a word: I suddenly realize that the complete arbitrariness of our language is but a part of the arbitrariness of our own world in general.', 47017, 0), (421640, 'Understanding is nothing else than conception caused by speech.', 2593, 0), (421641, 'Language is to the mind more than light is to the eye.', 9661, 0), (421642, 'Who does not know another language  does not know his own.', 62192, 0), (421643, 'To me  the term ''middle-class'' connotes a safe  comfortable  middle-of-the road policy. Above all  our language is ''middle-class'' in the middle of our road. To drive it to one side or the other or even off the road  is the noblest task of the future.', 47017, 0), (421644, 'Similes are like songs of love: They much describe  they nothing prove.', 7402, 0), (421645, 'Words are the physicians of a mind diseased.', 1882, 0), (421646, 'A language is a dialect with its own army and navy.', 66128, 0), (421647, '''When I use a word '' Humpty Dumpty said in rather a scornful tone  ''it means just what I choose it to mean - neither more nor less.'' ''The question is '' said Alice  ''whether you can make words mean so many different things.'' ''The question is '' said Humpty Dumpty  ''which is to be master - that''s all.''', 1253, 0), (421648, 'The word is half his that speaks  and half his that hears it.', 663, 0), (421649, 'A single word often betrays a great design.', 66129, 0), (421650, 'Words once spoken  can never be recalled.', 66122, 0);
INSERT INTO quotes (id, content, author_id, views) VALUES (421651, 'Some words are like the old Roman galleys  large-scaled and ponderous. They sit low in the water even when their cargo is light.', 62680, 0), (421652, 'It''s as interesting and as difficult to say a thing well as to paint it. There is the art of lines and colours  but the art of words exists too  and will never be less important.', 89, 0), (421653, 'The difference between the right word and the almost right word is the difference between lightning and the lightning bug.', 286, 0), (421654, 'Words  like eyeglasses  blur everything that they do not make clear.', 8895, 0), (421655, 'There is only one way to degrade mankind permanently and that is to destroy language.', 9817, 0), (421656, 'The art of writing is the art of discovering what you believe.', 9797, 0), (421657, 'The limits of my language mean the limits of my world.', 1163, 0), (421658, 'More than kisses  letters mingle souls.', 703, 0), (421659, 'I wonder what language truck drivers are using  now that everyone is using theirs?', 62277, 0), (421660, 'The two words ''information'' and ''communication'' are often used interchangeably  but they signify quite different things. Information is giving out  communication is getting through.', 4317, 0), (421661, 'England and America are two countries separated by the same language.', 266, 0), (421662, 'The Englishman loves to roll his tongue around the word  ''extraordinary''. It so pleases him that he is reluctant to finish the sound which goes on into harmonics and overtones. The North American publisher is likewise inclined.', 62689, 0), (421663, 'Words are feminine  deeds are masculine.', 1255, 0), (421664, 'Let it not be said that I have said nothing new. The arrangement of the material is new.', 144, 0), (421665, 'When an idea is wanting  a word can always be found to take its place.', 62192, 0), (421666, 'Speech is civilization itself. The word  even the most contradictory word  preserves contact - it is silence which isolates.', 778, 0), (421667, 'In certain trying circumstances  urgent circumstances  desperate circumstances  profanity furnishes a relief denied even to prayer.', 286, 0), (421668, 'Like stones  words are laborious and unforgiving  and the fitting of them together  like the fitting of stones  demands great patience and strength of purpose and particular skill.', 66130, 0), (421669, 'Great literature is simply language charged with meaning to the utmost possible degree.', 8630, 0), (421670, 'One way of looking at speech is to say it is a constant stratagem to cover nakedness.', 3174, 0), (421671, 'The downtrodden  who are the great creators of slang  hurl pithiness and colour at poverty and oppression.', 1132, 0), (421672, 'Slang is language which takes off its coat  spits on its hands - and goes to work.', 1301, 0), (421673, 'Man''s command of the language is most important. Next to kissing  it''s the most exciting form of communication.', 65142, 0), (421674, '"Plain English" - everybody loves it  demands it - from the other fellow.', 9596, 0), (421675, 'Words are as recalcitrant as circus animals  and the unskilled trainer can crack his whip at them in vain.', 38041, 0), (421676, 'The magic of the tongue is the most dangerous of all spells.', 5223, 0), (421677, 'A word after a word after a word is power.', 114, 0), (421678, 'You have to fall in love with hanging around words.', 12892, 0), (421679, 'Language is the armoury of the human mind  and at once contains the trophies of its past  and the weapons of its future conquests.', 1910, 0), (421680, 'Everyone hears only what he understands.', 62192, 0), (421681, 'When I feel inclined to read poetry  I take down my dictionary. The poetry of words is quite as beautiful as the poetry of sentences.', 24754, 0), (421682, 'Language most shows a man  speak that I may see thee.', 29394, 0), (421683, 'True eloquence consists of saying all that should be  not all that could be  said.', 62191, 0), (421684, 'Even if language is a living evolving organism  we don''t have to embrace all the changes that occur during our lifetimes. If language is so alive  it can get sick.', 66131, 0), (421685, 'Our language  one of our most precious natural resources  deserves at least as much protection as our woodlands  streams and whooping cranes.', 66132, 0), (421686, 'His words were softer than oil  yet they were drawn swords.', 5587, 0), (421687, 'Language is an inventory of human experience.', 66133, 0), (421688, 'Change is legitimate and inevitable  for our language is a mighty river  picking up silt and flotsam here and discarding it there  but growing ever wider and richer.', 66134, 0), (421689, 'The grossest thing in our gross national product today is our language. It is suffering from inflation.', 63554, 0), (421690, 'A word has its use  Or  like a man  it will soon have a grave.', 66135, 0), (421691, 'No matter how eloquently a dog may bark  he cannot tell you that his parents were poor but honest.', 95, 0), (421692, 'Most people have to talk so they won''t hear.', 996, 0), (421693, 'Every utterance is an event  and no two events are precisely alike. The extreme view  therefore  is that no word ever means the same thing twice.', 31317, 0), (421694, 'It is with words as with sunbeams. The more they are condensed  the deeper they burn.', 28307, 0), (421695, 'If you can teach me a new word  I''ll walk all the way to China to get it.', 57898, 0), (421696, 'I have always suspected that correctness is the last refuge of those who have nothing to say.', 66136, 0), (421697, 'By working faithfully eight hours a day you may eventually get to be a boss and work 12 hours a day.', 35, 0), (421698, 'Everything considered  work is less boring than amusing oneself.', 1165, 0), (421699, 'A windmill is eternally at work to accomplish one end  although it shifts with every variation of the weather cock  and assumes 10 different positions in a day.', 432, 0), (421700, 'A good horse should be seldom spurred.', 1348, 0);
INSERT INTO quotes (id, content, author_id, views) VALUES (421701, 'All work is seed sown. It grows and spreads  and sows itself anew.', 3061, 0), (421702, 'Chop your own wood and it will warm you twice.', 66137, 0), (421703, 'Give the labourer his wage before his perspiration be dry.', 62983, 0), (421704, 'I want a house that has gotten over all its troubles  I don''t want to spend the rest of my life bringing up a young and inexperienced house.', 2174, 0), (421705, 'If you want a work well done  select a busy man: the other kind has no time.', 4, 0), (421706, 'It is impossible to enjoy idling thoroughly unless one has plenty of work to do.', 2174, 0), (421707, 'Most people work the greater part of their time for a mere living  and the little freedom which remains to them so troubles them that they use every means of getting rid of it.', 62192, 0), (421708, 'Neither snow  nor rain  nor heat  nor gloom of night stay these couriers from the swift completion of their appointed rounds.', 1863, 0), (421709, 'No fine work can be done without concentration and self-sacrifice and toil and doubt.', 17074, 0), (421710, 'No task  rightly done is truly private. It is part of the world''s work.', 1970, 0), (421711, 'One machine can do the work of 50 ordinary men. No machine can do the work of one extraordinary man.', 33, 0), (421712, 'One of the saddest things is  the only thing a man can do for 8 hours a day  day after day  is work. You can''t eat 8 hours a day nor drink for 8 hours a day  nor make love for 8 hours.', 344, 0), (421713, 'The only place where success comes before work is a dictionary.', 65146, 0), (421714, 'Routine is the god of every social system  it is the seventh heaven of business  the essential component in the success of every factory  the ideal of every statesman.', 2606, 0), (421715, 'The monarchy is a labour-intensive industry.', 18461, 0), (421716, 'The test of a vocation is the love of the drudgery it involves.', 1014, 0), (421717, 'They say hard work never hurt anybody  but I figure why take the chance.', 1727, 0), (421718, 'Unionism  seldom if ever  uses such powers as it has to ensure better work  almost always it devotes a large part of that power to safeguarding bad work.', 411, 0), (421719, 'Work is of two kinds: first  altering a position of matter at or near the earth''s surface relatively to other such matter  second  telling other people to do so. The first kind is unpleasant and ill-paid  the second is pleasant and highly paid.', 95, 0), (421720, 'As a remedy against all ills - poverty  sickness  and melanchol - only one thing is absolutely necessary: a liking for work.', 1165, 0), (421721, 'They intoxicate themselves with work so they won''t see how they really are.', 1032, 0), (421722, 'Most people like hard work  particularly when they''re paying for it.', 62728, 0), (421723, 'We work to become  not to acquire.', 4, 0), (421724, 'If one defines the term ''dropout'' to mean a person who has given up serious effort to meet his responsibilities  then every business office  government agency  golf club and university faculty would yield its quota.', 11471, 0), (421725, 'Hasten slowly  and without losing heart  put your work twenty times upon the anvil.', 57320, 0), (421726, 'How many years of fatigue and punishment it takes to learn the simple truth that work  that disagreeable thing  is the only way of not suffering in life  or at all events  of suffering less.', 1165, 0), (421727, 'Miracles sometimes occur  but one has to work terribly hard for them.', 66138, 0), (421728, 'Beware all enterprises that require new clothes.', 1049, 0), (421729, 'Employment is nature''s physician  and is essential to human happiness.', 3262, 0), (421730, 'Work is the grand cure of all the maladies and miseries that ever beset mankind.', 3061, 0), (421731, 'The secret of being miserable is to have leisure to bother about whether you are happy or not. The cure for it is occupation.', 266, 0), (421732, 'Chance favours only those who know how to court her.', 66139, 0), (421733, 'Work is man''s most natural form of relaxation.', 62441, 0), (421734, 'Work is not man''s punishment. It is his reward and his strength  his glory and his pleasure.', 810, 0), (421735, 'If a man loves the labour of his trade  apart from any question of success or fame  the gods have called him.', 449, 0), (421736, 'When white-collar people get jobs  they sell not only their time and energy  but their personalities as well. They sell by week  or month  their smiles and their kindly gestures  and they must practise prompt repression of resentment and aggression.', 25219, 0), (421737, 'He that can work is a born king of something.', 3061, 0), (421738, 'Love of bustle is not industry.', 1379, 0), (421739, 'The joy about our work is spoiled when we perform it not because of what we produce but because of the pleasure with which it can provide us  or the pain against which it can protect us.', 2750, 0), (421740, 'Productive work is the central purpose of a rational man''s life  the central value that integrates and determines the hierarchy of all his other values. Reason is the source  the precondition of his productive work - pride is the result.', 631, 0), (421741, 'By the work one knows the workman.', 2843, 0), (421742, 'Because it is less structured than work  leisure time leaves workaholics at a loss for what to do. Workaholics practically climb the wall when they can''t work.', 63163, 0), (421743, 'Workaholics commit slow suicide by refusing to allow the child inside them to play.', 66140, 0), (421744, 'Man works primarily for his own self-respect and not for others or for profit. . . the person who is working for the sake of his own satisfaction  the money he gets in return serves merely as fuel  that is  as a symbol of reward and recognition  in the last analysis  of acceptance by one''s fellowmen.', 1819, 0), (421745, 'To travel hopefully is a better thing than to arrive  and the true success is to labour.', 449, 0), (421746, 'In a professional once engaged  the performance of the job comes first.', 7156, 0), (421747, 'If a little labour  little are our gains. Man''s fortunes are according to his pains.', 8674, 0), (421748, 'Work is the curse of the drinking classes.', 40, 0), (421749, 'A man must love a thing very much if he not only practises it without any hope of fame and money  but even practises it without any hope of doing it well.', 263, 0), (421750, 'A hobby is hard work you wouldn''t do for a living.', 33, 0);
INSERT INTO quotes (id, content, author_id, views) VALUES (421751, 'A task becomes a duty from the moment you suspect it to be an essential part of that integrity which alone entitles a man to assume responsibility.', 851, 0), (421752, 'God gave man work  not to burden him  but to bless him  and useful work  willingly  cheerfully  effectively done  has always been the finest expression of the human spirit.', 66141, 0), (421753, 'Work is more fun than fun.', 2896, 0), (421754, 'When more and more people are thrown out of work  unemployment results.', 4110, 0), (421755, 'Man''s usual routine is to work and to dream and work and dream.', 34376, 0), (421756, 'We can redeem anyone who strives unceasingly.', 62192, 0), (421757, 'The Gods rank work above virtues.', 3287, 0), (421758, 'Anyone can do any amount of work provided it isn''t the work he is supposed to be doing at that moment.', 2188, 0), (421759, 'It is not upon thee to finish the work  neither art thou free to abstain from it.', 62345, 0), (421760, 'Work banishes those three great evils  boredom  vice  and poverty.', 808, 0), (421761, 'Amateurs hope. Professionals work.', 7156, 0), (421762, 'Work is love made visible. And if you cannot work with love but only with distaste  it is better that you should leave your work and sit at the gate of the temple and take alms of those who work with joy.', 81, 0), (421763, 'There is dignity in work only when it is work freely accepted.', 532, 0), (421764, 'If a man will not work  he shall not eat.', 5587, 0), (421765, 'Anyone who is honestly seeking a job and can''t find it  deserves the attention of the United States government  and the people.', 1680, 0), (421766, 'Work is the inevitable condition of human life  the true source of human welfare.', 93, 0), (421767, 'He who shuns the millstone  shuns the meal.', 1966, 0), (421768, 'Rest is the sweet sauce of labour.', 4891, 0), (421769, 'God gives every bird its food  but he does not throw it into the nest.', 24989, 0), (421770, 'When your work speaks for itself  don''t interrupt.', 62342, 0), (421771, 'I work as my father drank.', 266, 0), (421772, 'While I am busy with little things  I am not required to do greater things.', 27065, 0), (421773, 'For it is commonly said: accomplished labours are pleasant.', 20928, 0), (421774, 'A people so primitive that they did not know how to get money except by working for it.', 9905, 0), (421775, 'Work expands so as to fill the time available for its completion.', 61019, 0), (421776, 'If all the year were playing holidays To sport would be as tedious as to work.', 13, 0), (421777, 'I am only an average man  but  by George  I work harder at it than the average man.', 1674, 0), (421778, 'Work is accomplished by those employees who have not yet reached their level of incompetence.', 2120, 0), (421779, 'When I was a young man I observed that nine out of ten things I did were failures. I didn''t want to be a failure  so I did ten times more work.', 266, 0), (421780, 'The worst crime against working people is a company which fails to operate at a profit.', 66142, 0), (421781, 'How do I work? I grope.', 104, 0), (421782, 'It is the privilege of any human work which is well done to invest the doer with a certain haughtiness. He can well afford not to conciliate  whose faithful work will answer for him.', 760, 0), (421783, 'Work and love - these are the basics. Without them there is neurosis.', 29103, 0), (421784, 'The effectiveness of work increases according to geometric progression if there are no interruptions.', 62434, 0), (421785, 'The road to happiness lies in two simple principles: find what it is that interests you and that you can do well  and when you find it  put your whole soul into it-every bit of energy and ambition and natural ability you have.', 64191, 0), (421786, 'Every woman is a human being-one cannot repeat that too often-and a human being must have occupation if he or she is not to become a nuisance to the world.', 3165, 0), (421787, 'The happy people are those who are producing something.', 4228, 0), (421788, 'Congenial labor is essence of happiness.', 62857, 0), (421789, 'Work is a substitute "religious" experience for many workaholics.', 1492, 0), (421790, 'When I can no longer create anything  I''ll be done for.', 111, 0), (421791, 'Employment is nature''s physician  and is essential to human happiness.', 3262, 0), (421792, 'No thoroughly occupied man was ever yet very miserable.', 10875, 0), (421793, 'When I stop [working]  the rest of the day is posthumous. I''m only really alive when I''m working.', 355, 0), (421794, 'Continuity of purpose is one of the most essential ingredients of happiness in the long run  and for most men this comes chiefly through their work.', 95, 0), (421795, 'It is only when I am doing my work that I feel truly alive. It is like having sex.', 19735, 0), (421796, 'After fifty years of living  it occurs to me that the most significant thing that people do is go to work  whether it is to go to work on their novel or at the assembly plant or fixing somebody''s teeth.', 4685, 0), (421797, 'He who labors diligently need never despair  for all things are accomplished by diligence and labor.', 31012, 0), (421798, 'The fun of being alive is realizing that you have a talent and you can use it every day  so it grows stronger. ... And if you''re in an atmosphere where this talent is appreciated instead of just tolerated  why  it''s just as good as sex.', 65527, 0), (421799, 'Work! Thank God for the swing of it  for the clamoring  hammering ring of it.', 33, 0), (421800, 'There are certain natures to whom work is nothing  the act of work everything.', 10610, 0);
INSERT INTO quotes (id, content, author_id, views) VALUES (421801, 'I am fierce for work. Without work I am nothing.', 28298, 0), (421802, 'Like plowing  housework makes the ground ready for the germination of family life. The kids will not invite a teacher home if beer cans litter the living room. The family isn''t likely to have breakfast together if somebody didn''t remember to buy eggs  milk  or muffins. Housework maintains an orderly setting in which family life can flourish.', 24198, 0), (421803, 'When I die  my epitaph should read: She Paid the Bills.', 49634, 0), (421804, 'There''s no labor a man can do that''s undignified  if he does it right.', 2059, 0), (421805, 'Never turn down a job because you think it''s too small  you never know where it may lead.', 66143, 0), (421806, 'If a man is called to be a streetsweep-er  he should sweep streets even as Michelangelo painted  or Beethoven composed music or Shakespeare wrote poetry. He should sweep streets so well that all the hosts of heaven and earth will pause to say  here lived a great streetsweeper who did his job well.', 21767, 0), (421807, 'Don''t be afraid of hard work.', 7224, 0), (421808, 'The work praises the man.', 25297, 0), (421809, 'Originality and the feeling of one''s own dignity are achieved only through work and struggle.', 57, 0), (421810, 'There is a kind of victory in good work  no matter how humble.', 66144, 0), (421811, 'Labor disgraces no man  unfortunately  you occasionally find men who disgrace labor.', 9689, 0), (421812, 'Honest labor bears a lovely face.', 18697, 0), (421813, 'I have friends in overalls whose friendship I would not swap for the favor of the kings of the world.', 1673, 0), (421814, 'The world is moved not only by the mighty shoves of the heroes  but also by the aggregate of the tiny pushes of each honest worker.', 701, 0), (421815, 'A professional is someone who can do his best work when he doesn''t feel like it.', 48832, 0), (421816, 'The highest reward for man''s toil is not what he gets for it  but what he becomes by it.', 485, 0), (421817, 'Starting out to make money is the greatest mistake in life. Do what you feel you have a flair for doing  and if you are good enough at it  the money will come.', 65526, 0), (421818, 'Ambition is destruction  only competence matters.', 64009, 0), (421819, 'I was brought up to believe that the only thing worth doing was to add to the sum of accurate information in the world.', 992, 0), (421820, 'Never desert your own line of talent. Be what nature intended you for  and you will succeed.', 9771, 0), (421821, 'Here I am  where I ought to be.', 43, 0), (421822, 'To find in ourselves what makes life worth living is risky business  for it means that once we know we must seek it. It also means that without it life will be valueless.', 65522, 0), (421823, 'Everybody undertakes what he sees another successful in  whether he has the aptitude for it or not.', 62224, 0), (421824, 'You have to do what you love to do  not get stuck in that comfort zone of a regular job. Life is not a dress rehearsal. This is it.', 66145, 0), (421825, 'Men take only their needs into consideration  never their abilities.', 1702, 0), (421826, 'If you''re in a good profession  it''s hard to get bored  because you''re never finished-there will always be work you haven''t done.', 1537, 0), (421827, 'Work means so many things! So many! Among other things  work also means freedom. ... Without it even the miracle of love is only a cruel deception.', 63815, 0), (421828, 'One should stick to the sort of thing for which one was made  I tried to be an herbalist  whereas I should keep to the butcher''s trade.', 2843, 0), (421829, 'One''s lifework  I have learned  grows with the working and the living. Do it as if your life depended on it  and first thing you know  you''ll have made a life out of it. A good life  too.', 62956, 0), (421830, 'One principal reason why men are so often useless is that they neglect their own profession or calling  and divide and shift their attention among a multitude of objects and pursuits.', 63998, 0), (421831, 'Men whose trade is rat-catching love to catch rats  the bug destroyer seizes on his bug with delight  the suppressor is gratified by finding his vice.', 9771, 0), (421832, 'Work is creativity accompanied by the comforting realization that one is bringing forth something really good and necessary  with a conviction that a sudden  arbitrary cessation would cause a sensitive void  produce a loss.', 66146, 0), (421833, 'Some people are born to lift heavy weights  some are born to juggle golden balls.', 17074, 0), (421834, 'Life is to be lived. If you have to support yourself  you had bloody well better find some way that is going to be interesting. And you don''t do that by sitting around wondering about yourself.', 205, 0), (421835, 'To find out what one is fitted to do  and to secure an opportunity to do it  is the key to happiness.', 2575, 0), (421836, 'The high prize of life  the crowning fortune of man  is to be born with a bias to some pursuit which finds him in employment and happiness.', 760, 0), (421837, 'They are happy men whose natures sort with their vocations.', 1035, 0), (421838, 'I know a lot of people think it''s monotonous  down the black lines over and over  but it''s not if you''re enjoying what you''re doing. I love to swim and I love to train.', 66147, 0), (421839, 'Do your duty until it becomes your joy.', 20540, 0), (421840, 'Duty is an icy shadow. It will freeze you. It cannot fill the heart''s sanctuary.', 66148, 0), (421841, 'What a richly colored strong warm coat is woven when love is the warp and work is the woof.', 8930, 0), (421842, 'Whenever it is possible  a boy should choose some occupation which he should do even if he did not need the money.', 6067, 0), (421843, 'Some people regard discipline as a chore. For me  it is a kind of order that sets me free to fly.', 62854, 0), (421844, 'Find something you''re passionate about and keep tremendously interested in it.', 1537, 0), (421845, 'There must be bands of enthusiasts for everything on earth-fanatics who shared a vocabulary  a batch of technical skills and equipment  and  perhaps  a vision of some single slice of the beauty and mystery of things  of their complexity  fascination  and unexpectedness.', 1173, 0), (421846, 'I love Mickey Mouse more than any woman I''ve ever known.', 65266, 0), (421847, 'The test of a vocation is the love of the drudgery it involves.', 1014, 0), (421848, 'Only he is successful in his business who makes that pursuit which affords him the highest pleasure sustain him.', 1049, 0), (421849, 'Work is a world apart from jobs. Work is the way you occupy your mind and hand and eye and whole body when they''re informed by your imagination.', 24969, 0), (421850, 'I believe in my work and in the joy of it. You have to be with the work and the work has to be with you. It absorbs you totally and you absorb it totally.', 51621, 0);
INSERT INTO quotes (id, content, author_id, views) VALUES (421851, 'Cooking is like love. It should be entered into with abandon or not at all.', 66149, 0), (421852, 'Give me a man who sings at his work.', 3061, 0), (421853, 'To love what you do and feel that it matters-how could anything be more fun?', 25066, 0), (421854, 'When men are rightly occupied  their amusement grows out of their work  as the color-petals out of a fruitful flower.', 485, 0), (421855, 'When love and skill work together  expect a masterpiece.', 485, 0), (421856, 'Work consists of whatever a body is obliged to do  and play consists of whatever a body is not obliged to do.', 286, 0), (421857, 'Winning the [Nobel] prize wasn''t half as exciting as doing the work itself.', 24922, 0), (421858, 'Work and play are words used to describe the same thing under differing conditions.', 286, 0), (421859, 'When people go to work  they shouldn''t have to leave their hearts at home.', 65542, 0), (421860, 'Workaholics are energized rather than enervated by their work-their energy paradoxically expands as it is expended.', 63163, 0), (421861, 'The more I want to get something done  the less I call it work.', 424, 0), (421862, 'To deny we need and want power is to deny that we hope to be effective.', 16440, 0), (421863, 'Success depends in a very large measure upon individual initiative and exertion  and cannot be achieved except by a dint of hard work.', 5934, 0), (421864, 'Nothing worthwhile comes easily. Half effort does not produce half results  it produces no results. Work  continuous work and hard work  is the only way to accomplish results that last.', 65851, 0), (421865, 'If a man wakes up famous  he hasn''t been sleeping.', 65852, 0), (421866, 'Striving for success without hard work is like trying to harvest where you haven''t planted.', 65854, 0), (421867, 'If your dream is a big dream  and if you want your life to work on the high level that you say you do  there''s no way around doing the work it takes to get you there.', 16466, 0), (421868, 'Success is dependent on effort.', 139, 0), (421869, 'Hard work has made it easy. That is my secret. That is why I win.', 14526, 0), (421870, 'Success comes before work only in the dictionary.', 33, 0), (421871, 'Sweat plus sacrifice equals success.', 65855, 0), (421872, 'The only thing that separates successful people from the ones who aren''t is the willingness to work very  very hard.', 2277, 0), (421873, 'You can have unbelievable intelligence  you can have connections  you can have opportunities fall out of the sky. But in the end  hard work is the true  enduring characteristic of successful people.', 66150, 0), (421874, 'Success usually comes to those who are too busy to be looking for it.', 1049, 0), (421875, 'In all human affairs there are efforts  there are results  and the strength of the effort is the measure of the result.', 14092, 0), (421876, 'Work  alternated with needful rest  is the salvation of man or woman.', 63990, 0), (421877, 'There is a time for work. And a time for love. That leaves no other time.', 111, 0), (421878, 'Neither woman nor man lives by work  or love  alone.... The human self defines itself and grows through love and work: All psychology before and after Freud boils down to that.', 1773, 0), (421879, 'Maintain a good balance. A personal life adds dimensions to your professional life and vice versa. It helps nurture creativity through a deeper understanding of yourself.', 64010, 0), (421880, 'For the happiest life  days should be rigorously planned  nights left open to chance.', 1932, 0), (421881, 'Work is the province of cattle.', 201, 0), (421882, 'The only sin passion can commit is to be joyless.', 3165, 0), (421883, 'Skilled labor teaches something not to be found in books or in colleges.', 66151, 0), (421884, 'Diligence is the mother of good luck  and God gives all things to industry.', 1077, 0), (421885, 'To industry  nothing is impossible.', 62593, 0), (421886, 'I believe in hard work. It keeps the wrinkles out of the mind and spirit.', 18698, 0), (421887, 'God sells us all things at the price of labor.', 1386, 0), (421888, 'The sport I love has taken me around the world and shown me many things.', 63991, 0), (421889, 'I realized that with hard work  the world was your oyster. You could do anything you wanted to do. I learned that at a young age.', 62310, 0), (421890, 'Fortune is ever seen accompanying industry.', 2204, 0), (421891, 'Manual labor to my father was not only good and decent for its own sake  but as he was given to saying  it straightened out one''s thoughts.', 10111, 0), (421892, 'I get satisfaction of three kinds. One is creating something  one is being paid for it and one is the feeling that I haven''t just been sitting on my ass all afternoon.', 64070, 0), (421893, 'The sentimentalist ages far more quickly than the person who loves his work and enjoys new challenges.', 5328, 0), (421894, 'Busy people are never busybodies.', 62687, 0), (421895, 'What a man sows  that shall he and his relations reap.', 66152, 0), (421896, 'The only way to enjoy anything in this life is to earn it first.', 28277, 0), (421897, 'I have worked all my life  wanted to work all my life  needed to work all my life.', 63115, 0), (421898, 'The simple idea that everyone needs a reasonable amount of challenging work in his or her life  and also a personal life  complete with noncompetitive leisure  has never really taken hold.', 6430, 0), (421899, 'There is no more dreadful punishment than futile and hopeless labor.', 532, 0), (421900, 'Whether we call it a job or a career  work is more than just something we do. It is a part of who we are.', 66153, 0);
INSERT INTO quotes (id, content, author_id, views) VALUES (421901, 'If I could I would always work in silence and obscurity  and let my efforts be known by their results.', 55, 0), (421902, 'Nobody ever drowned in his own sweat.', 3199, 0), (421903, 'The heights by great men reached and kept Were not attained by sudden flight  But they  while their companions slept  Were toiling upward in the night.', 147, 0), (421904, 'Work in some form or other is the appointed lot of all.', 63997, 0), (421905, 'Any man who has had the job I''ve had and didn''t have a sense of humor wouldn''t still be here.', 16121, 0), (421906, 'Whatever the job you are asked to do at whatever level  do a good job because your reputation is your resume.', 17868, 0), (421907, 'People should tell their children what life is all about-it''s about work.', 12702, 0), (421908, 'Marriage ain''t easy but nothing that''s worth much ever is.', 63321, 0), (421909, 'I don''t think that work ever really destroyed anybody. I think that lack of work destroys them a hell of a lot more.', 205, 0), (421910, 'For the last third of life there remains only work. It alone is always stimulating  rejuvenating  exciting and satisfying.', 4835, 0), (421911, 'I slept  and dreamed that life was Beauty  I woke  and found that life was Duty.', 66154, 0), (421912, 'Passion is never enough  neither is skill.', 171, 0), (421913, 'It''s not the having  it''s the getting.', 1553, 0), (421914, 'Opportunity is missed by most people because it is dressed in overalls  and looks like work.', 1673, 0), (421915, 'A man''s work is from sun to sun  but a mother''s work is never done.', 33, 0), (421916, 'Be strong! We are not here to play  to dream  to drift  We have hard work to do and loads to lift  Shun not the struggle-face it  ''tis God''s gift.', 63768, 0), (421917, 'If you could once make up your mind never to undertake more work ... than you can carry on calmly  quietly  without hurry or flurry ... and if the instant you feel yourself growing nervous and ... out of breath  you would stop and take a breath  you would find this simple common-sense rule doing for you what no prayers or tears could ever accomplish.', 24226, 0), (421918, 'It is better to have no emotion when it is work. Do what needs to be done  and do it coolly.', 1682, 0), (421919, 'What a man accomplishes in a day depends upon the way in which he approaches his tasks. When we accept tough jobs as a challenge to our ability and wade into them with joy and enthusiasm  miracles can happen. When we do our work with a dynamic  conquering spirit  we get things done.', 62236, 0), (421920, 'The one important thing I have learned over the years is the difference between taking one''s work seriously  and taking one''s self seriously. The first is imperative  and the second is disastrous.', 49689, 0), (421921, 'Work is the best method devised for killing time.', 5249, 0), (421922, 'Industry is a better horse to ride than genius.', 41371, 0), (421923, 'There are two kinds of talents  man-made talent and God-given talent. With man-made talent you have to work very hard. With God-given talent  you just touch it up once in a while.', 27040, 0), (421924, 'If you want something done  ask a busy person to do it. The more things you do  the more you can do.', 1814, 0), (421925, 'With the power of conviction  there is no sacrifice.', 18685, 0), (421926, 'I believe you are your work. Don''t trade the stuff of your life  time  for nothing more than dollars. That''s a rotten bargain', 138, 0), (421927, 'When you''re following your energy and doing what you want all the time  the distinction between work and play dissolves.', 39554, 0), (421928, 'Work is the thing that stays. Work is the thing that sees us through.', 34669, 0), (421929, 'Energy is the power that drives every human being. It is not lost by exertion but maintained by it  for it is a faculty of the psyche.', 1413, 0), (421930, 'It is not hard work that is dreary  it is superficial work', 749, 0), (421931, 'As for me  prizes mean nothing. My prize is my work.', 205, 0), (421932, 'There can be no substitute for work  neither affection nor physical well-being can replace it.', 11408, 0), (421933, 'Work is its own cure. You have to like it better than being loved.', 8930, 0), (421934, 'Work ... has always been my favorite form of recreation.', 66155, 0), (421935, 'A job is not a career. I think I started out with a job. It turned into a career and changed my life.', 64122, 0), (421936, 'The only genius that''s worth anything is the genius for hard work.', 18900, 0), (421937, 'Elbow grease is the best polish.', 41936, 0), (421938, 'Never despair  but if you do  work on in despair.', 2026, 0), (421939, 'Laziness is a secret ingredient that goes into failure. But it''s only kept a secret from the person who fails.', 2423, 0), (421940, 'Pears cannot ripen alone. So we ripened together.', 63764, 0), (421941, 'Ideally  couples need three lives  one for him  one for her  and one for them together.', 18672, 0), (421942, 'Exchange is creation.', 1736, 0), (421943, 'Whatever my individual desires were to be free  I was not alone. There were others who felt the same way.', 19482, 0), (421944, 'Now men and women are separate and unequal. We should be hand in hand  in fact  we should have our arms around one another.', 66156, 0), (421945, 'Men and women are like right and left hands: it doesn''t make sense not to use both.', 16068, 0), (421946, 'There are three ways of dealing with difference: domination  compromise  and integration. By domination only one side gets what it wants  by compromise neither side gets what it wants  by integration we find a way by which both sides may get what they wish.', 62311, 0), (421947, 'Women and men have to fight together to change society-and both will benefit.', 65241, 0), (421948, 'Every time a man unburdens his heart to a stranger he reaffirms the love that unites humanity.', 1413, 0), (421949, 'Good communication is as stimulating as black coffee  and just as hard to sleep after.', 1407, 0), (421950, 'Cooperation is an intelligent functioning of the concept of laissez faire-a thorough conviction that nobody can get there unless everybody gets there.', 65555, 0);
INSERT INTO quotes (id, content, author_id, views) VALUES (421951, 'Most leaders are indispensable  but to produce a major social change  many ordinary people must also be involved.', 66157, 0), (421952, 'Communication is a continual balancing act  juggling the conflicting needs for intimacy and independence. To survive in the world  we have to act in concert with others  but to survive as ourselves  rather than simply as cogs in a wheel  we have to act alone.', 41330, 0), (421953, 'My whole life  whether it be long or short  shall be devoted to your service and the service of our great imperial family to which we all belong. But I shall not have the strength to carry out this resolution alone unless you join in it with me.', 65677, 0), (421954, 'A person who believes ... that there is a whole of which one is a part  and that in being a part one is whole: such a person has no desire whatever  at any time  to play God. Only those who have denied their being yearn to play at it.', 62247, 0), (421955, 'Unless I am a part of everything I am nothing.', 11995, 0), (421956, 'For what is done or learned by one class of women becomes  by virtue of their common womanhood  the property of all women.', 38126, 0), (421957, 'We learn best to listen to our own voices if we are listening at the same time to other women-whose stories  for all our differences  turn out  if we listen well  to be our stories also.', 49452, 0), (421958, 'Remember the dignity of your womanhood. Do not appeal  do not beg  do not grovel. Take courage  join hands  stand beside us  fight with us.', 65683, 0), (421959, 'Today whenever women gather together it is not necessarily nurturing. It is coalition building. And if you feel the strain  you may be doing some good work.', 63137, 0), (421960, 'Women''s art  though created in solitude  wells up out of community. There is  clearly  both enormous hunger for the work thus being diffused  and an explosion of creative energy  bursting through the coercive choicelessness of the system on whose boundaries we are working.', 809, 0), (421961, 'You''ve got to be willing to stay committed to someone over the long run  and sometimes it doesn''t work out. But often if you become real honest with yourself and honest with each other  and put aside whatever personal hurt and disappointment you have to really understand yourself and your spouse  it can be the most wonderful experience you''ve ever had.', 10130, 0), (421962, 'We must stand together  if we don''t  there will be no victory for any one of us.', 65862, 0), (421963, 'I''ve always believed that one woman''s success can only help another woman''s success.', 5883, 0), (421964, 'Alone we can do so little  together we can do so much.', 701, 0), (421965, 'I always feel the movement is a sort of mosaic. Each of us puts in one little stone  and then you get a great mosaic at the end.', 64860, 0), (421966, 'We all act as hinges-fortuitous links between other people.', 11995, 0), (421967, 'We seldom stop to think how many people''s lives are entwined with our own. It is a form of selfishness to imagine that every individual can operate on his own or can pull out of the general stream and not be missed.', 51389, 0), (421968, 'When Adam dolve  and Eve span  Who was then the gentleman?', 52004, 0), (421969, 'Better to wear out than to rust out.', 66158, 0), (421970, 'The workers are the saviors of society  the redeemers of the race.', 10499, 0), (421971, 'Handle your tools without mittens.', 1077, 0), (421972, 'Tools were made and born were hands  Every farmer understands.', 221, 0), (421973, 'I never did anything worth doing by accident  nor did any of my inventions come by accident  they came by work.', 63927, 0), (421974, 'It''s all in the day''s work.', 62710, 0), (421975, 'A ploughman on his legs is higher than a gentleman on his knees.', 1077, 0), (421976, 'In the sweat of thy face shalt thou eat bread.', 5587, 0), (421977, 'All work and no play makes Jack a dull boy.', 44934, 0), (421978, 'I like work  it fascinates me. I can sit and look at it for hours. I love to keep it by me: the idea of getting rid of it nearly breaks my heart.', 2174, 0), (421979, 'And only the Master shall praise us  and only the Master shall blame  And no one shall work for money  and no one shall work for fame  But each for the joy of the working  and each  in his separate star  Shall draw the Thing as he sees It  for the God of things as They Are!', 843, 0), (421980, 'No man is born into the world whose work Is not born with him  there is always work  And tools to work withal  for those who will  And blessed are the horny hands of toil!', 1247, 0), (421981, 'The laborer is worthy of his hire.', 5587, 0), (421982, 'How many a rustic Milton has passed by  Stifling the speechless longings of his heart  In unremitting drudgery and care! How many a vulgar Cato has compelled His energies  no longer tameless then  To mould a pin  or fabricate a nail!', 165, 0), (421983, 'Many hands make light work.', 66159, 0), (421984, 'Heaven is blessed with perfect rest but the blessing of earth is toil.', 672, 0), (421985, 'This is the best world  that we live in  To lend and to spend and to give in: But to borrow  or beg  or to get a man''s own  It is the worst world that ever was known.', 33, 0), (421986, 'This world''s a bubble.', 62421, 0), (421987, 'Believe everything you hear said of the world  nothing is too impossibly bad.', 143, 0), (421988, 'The world is like a board with holes in it  and the square men have got into the round holes  and the round into the square.', 66078, 0), (421989, 'The pomps and vanity of this wicked world.', 5587, 0), (421990, 'But in this world nothing is sure but death and taxes.', 1077, 0), (421991, 'The year''s at the Spring And day''s at the morn  Morning''s at seven  The hillside''s dew-pearled  The lark''s on the wing  The snail''s on the thorn: God''s in his Heaven -  All''s right with the world!', 157, 0), (421992, 'I have not loved the world